segments.text: This is a test.
This is Terry Anderson.
Today's date is April 8, 1980.
This is the second interview with Dr. Patton Burns of the Vet School on the Vet Medicine Project.
This is a test.
This is the second interview
But Dr. Burns, last time we ended our first interview talking about Dr. Mark Francis, and this time I'd like to continue talking about personalities that you were involved with over the years.
Do you have anything else to say about Mark Francis, or should we move on to others?
I don't recall.
Well, you were saying about the greatest man that you knew.
Yes.
Of course he did his world of experience in extension work, experimentation work primarily, and teaching.
And he was it, of course, up until sixteen.
But there's no end of stories about him.
He was quite an interesting person.
What about Ross Perry Marsteller?
Well, yes.
Dr. Marsteller came, I said, not until 16.
I made a mistake there.
Dr. Marsteller graduated from Ohio State University and came to Texas in 1905, I believe, to help Dr. Francis.
In fact, from the time I knew it, from my experience from 23 on, Dr. Marsteller took care of more of the academics.
And Dr. Francis, of course, taught anatomy and had the title of dean.
But Dr. Marsteller did more of the work
More the administration?
Yes, oh yes.
Why was that?
Was he a better administrator do you think?
No, probably because of Dr. Francis' difficulty in hearing.
Oh, I see.
And Dr. Marston enjoyed meeting people and he knew
I think practically every mother and father of every student he ever had.
It was more of a family proposition.
What kind of person was Marsteller?
Well, he was a very good teacher and I think a good administrator.
Some of the students didn't like him.
I think the majority of us did.
Why didn't they like him?
I think because he was quite harsh with them for a purpose.
I think if they would have acceded to his advice, they would have been better off.
In what way was he harsh?
Well, he'd get on some pretty hard about that dress.
wearing overalls and coveralls and things like that that he thought they should dress properly.
Did he have a dress code?
We didn't have any uniform code.
We didn't have any dress code.
Oh, you didn't.
But he wanted them to look neatly and it was for their own good.
I think he was, he has a, pardon me,
As a hobby, of course, he was quite interested in horses.
And he was an early riser, and he spent many, many hours at the veterinary hospital.
I know he took his lunch.
And Dr. Walton, who was president from 25 on, said that, told him he must be a poor administrator if he couldn't get time to go home and get a meal.
why he must not have his work organized properly.
But that was it.
How do you think Marsteller got along with Dr. Francis?
Fine, fine.
Oh, I don't think anyone ever failed to get along with Dr. Francis.
He was just that type of individual.
Yes, that is right.
Dr. Marsteller was harder to get along with, but I worked under him.
In what way?
Well, his personality.
I might call him moody at times, but I could see it sometimes.
I could tell when he walked in the front door in the morning.
And I guess probably I was the first one he saw, and he was the first one I saw because it was so early.
And I lived in the hospital, but I could tell and watch him during the day, and I'd know when to
and not to cross him with anything, and so.
How'd you get along with him?
Fine, I got along with him fine.
But I never had any trouble with any administrators.
We had, fortunately, enough to have some very good administrators.
I know when Dr. Francis died, there was some rumbling among some of the former students that they wanted
somebody else from outside for dean.
And I told them, I said, you're spinning your wheels.
I said, the dean has already been selected.
Well, I had talked to Dr. Walton about it.
And so I could tell that he was going to make his choice.
And he was leaning to Dr. Marsteller.
highly recommended Dr. Marsteller.
Of course, he didn't ask me for my recommendation, but he just asked for my opinion, getting a student's viewpoint.
And, oh well, I was on the staff then, too, when that happened.
And talked to a number, and he was made acting dean in fall of 36, and in 37, he was made dean.
He was on a trial basis, I guess.
did the same thing he'd been doing for years.
They were thinking, though, about going to the outside, maybe back to Ohio State or something?
Some of the former students, several of whom didn't care too much about Dr. Marsteller, but it was a personality clash.
They'd had trouble with him somewhere along the way.
And it was, I guess they figured there was a time to howl.
I told some of them, I said, you may as well quiet down.
I said, I think he's already been selected.
I said, I'm not saying that he has been, but I feel pretty sure that Dr. Marshall is going to be our dean.
And I said, at the time that I thought he'd make a good one, and I thought he did.
Of course, then he got in bad health.
Well, speaking of the former students, these were individuals, though.
This wasn't the former student association, was it?
No, no, no, no association.
Has the former students, now that we're on this, has the former students association ever had any input into the administration of the vet school that you can remember?
Not that I recall, not at all.
Okay, now let's talk about Ralph Dunn.
Well, he was...
Because of Dr. Marsteller's health, he resigned as dean, and he had gone to Mayo's in Rochester.
Oh, he did.
He went to the Mayo Clinic.
Yes, Mayo Clinic for surgery.
What health problem did he have?
Well, thyroid, and he had, I think, let it go a little too long, and I think that's one thing that perhaps influenced his
or affected his personality, but not to a severe degree as far as I was concerned.
But when you got up there, you got time to think about it more, and he stayed some time.
I don't recall how long, but he never was in too good health from then on.
So he relinquished the duties and Dean Bowden came in in 48, Dr. Dunn was in Dean in 47, 48 I think, yes.
For about one year.
Yeah, one year.
And then they brought in Dr. Bowden who was in research at Sonora Experiment Station.
Dr. Boughton graduated in Ohio State in 1916, and then spent one year coaching football.
He had been captain of the football team up there, and he was coaching the line in 1916, 17, and then he decided to go on with graduate work, and he went to the University of Illinois.
and in research work.
And from there he went to Haiti and for I believe in 1925 and he was there and there until 31.
In 31, 32 he took graduate work back at Ohio State.
He was just biding his time until some offer came along.
Then the opportunity of that experiment station job at Sonora opened up.
He started there in 1932 and remained there until 1948.
I feel pretty sure that Dr. Dunn was dean under one year, maybe a year and a half, something like that.
What kind of man was Dr. Dunn?
Rather reserved, quiet.
He'd spent his time, he came here in 1911, I believe.
He was a graduate of Ohio State.
He was in, took care of the
hard collar serum laboratory.
At that time they made whole blood hard collar.
The private institutions took that over and made a serum rather than whole blood.
The college discontinued
the use of the hog collar work.
And then Dr. Dunn switched to poultry.
And he was a very good man in poultry science.
And they made old chicken pox vaccine.
I know one summer when I, in summer of 25, he was gone for a month or two.
And they turned the job of making that chicken pox vaccine over to me and filling orders and things like that.
And so I got to know Dr. Dunn's work pretty well that way.
He was a good man.
What kind of teacher was he?
Very good.
Good lecturer.
But I don't know, unless he wasn't entirely sold.

The administration wanted to put in, wanted to, at that time, the administration wanted to combine extension work, agricultural extension work, agricultural experimentation, and the teaching all in one.
And Dr. Boughton implemented that, and he did that work and did a good job of it.
I don't know unless some of them doubted that Dr. Dunn was sold on the idea of combining them.
Some people were against it, some few.
And it all turned out for the good.
But I don't know what happened, but they...
brought Dr. Boughton in.
Yeah, doesn't it seem rather odd that Dr. Dunn would be here almost three decades and then they'd appoint him dean.
He'd only last one year and then I think he went to Florida.
No, he He left in 1948, didn't he, after one year of being the dean?
He married the former secretary
in the School of Under-Medicine, Minnie Dunn, and she had inherited a farm down here around Wellborn, American, and he just resigned and started working down there at home.
He just became a private citizen around here.
I don't ever recall him going to Florida.
Oh, then I mixed up.
But nevertheless, he still, after just having that job for one year, all of a sudden resigns.
And he wasn't that old.
He wasn't in his 60s.
I understand he was rather bitter about it, but I don't know any particulars.
I know only the good parts about him.
Did he set up his own clinic?
No.
So he just had his own ranch.
He just dropped all of his activities in veterinary medicine.
How about Dr. Schmidt?
Dr. Schmidt I think was influenced in taking veterinary medicine here.
At the University of Berlin, Dr. Francis had him in class, as all agricultural students did.
Dr. Schmidt finished here, I think, in 1908 or 7, 8, I believe.
Yes, because then Dr. Francis was responsible for him having gone to University of Berlin.
because he was brought up around Comfort, in Comfort, west of San Antonio, and German descent.
In fact, he had quite a brogue.
I don't know whether he ever talked any English at home.
But he went to
Berlin, and took four years of veterinary medicine, finished in 12, and came back here and married a native of Berlin.
And she's still living here in Bryan.
Oh, really?
What's her name?
Gertrude Schmidt, S-C-H-M-I-D-T. She's a patient in Bryan Hospital.
She had a stroke, severe stroke, about a year or two ago.
and she's in a coma.
Oh, she is?
Semicomatose, yes.
They say that she can recognize you with her eyes, but the paralysis says she looks much younger and no wrinkles.
She has a beautiful complexion.
And they say she still has it.
And he brought her back from Berlin?
I don't know whether they married over there or I think she came over here and then they married over in the States.
But he was implied to help Dr. Francis with a tick problem.
and with the inoculation of calves in the wintertime for Texas tick fever.
He was, Dr. Francis officially was Director of the Vendor Division of the Aero-Cushion Experiment Station.
entitled, but Dr. Schmidt did the work.
And then following Dr. Francis' death in 36, Dr. Schmidt was continued as he became administrator of the veterinary division.
Did you ever have him for classes?
No, he didn't do any teaching.
See, they were separate by that time.
Did you ever work with him?
Oh, his office was right, my office was right above Dr. Francis.
I was on the second floor.
Dr. Schmidt was on the third floor.
His office was right above me.
So we saw each other every day when he was in town.
He did a lot of, well, it's extension work himself, mostly experimentation, but some of that work was in West Texas.
He might be gone for a week or two.
Say poisonous plants problem would be in the,
Edwards Plateau region or in the Big Bend or around Pecos.
So he'd be gone for sometimes a week or two more at a time.
But he was in an automobile accident on this Curtin Road and some man turned into the road and he never recovered.
That was, he lived to be
71 or 71 and a half.
Dr. Mesthal, I think, was 71.
Dr. Francis, 73.
What kind of man was Dr. Schmidt?
He was a great big, he had been a football player here.
Really?
I don't think he'd ever seen a football or touched a football until he got to A&M.
And he, I guess it was a guard or tackle, I don't recall, but he was a big man and strong, very strong.
But he got a little arthritis in his last few years, but it slowed him down a little bit, but he was still a strong man.
He owned a place out on Curtin Road, and oh, I think they're finding that oil

area and she sold it after that and he he had gone into uh he cooperated a great deal with the king ranch and uh but down there quite a bit of the time and uh he went in the santa gertrudis business and uh had some excellent santa gertrudis cattle and when he died and uh
So somebody realized the value of those cattle.
Mrs. Smith was going to sell them market price.
And somebody realized that they were worth more than that.
So someone had Dr. Jimmy Northway to come up from the King Ranch, the veterinarian down there, to evaluate them.
And it saved her a lot of money.
But she sold them at a good price.
but unfortunately sold the land a little bit too soon.
Because of the oil.
Well, the prices of land in general over the county, too.
How about Dr. Van Valkenburgh?
Dr. Van Valkenburgh was brought in here from, in 1936,
I believe in 1937 the Department of Parasitology was organized.
At the same time that the Veterinary Hygiene was organized.
And I know Jackie came up from Beaumont.
He had the job, took the job that I had at Beaumont when I came back up here.
And Dr. Kerr asked me, I was with Dr. Kerr, and he asked me if anyone I could recommend.
Heard that Dr. Jagger wasn't too happy with his job in New Orleans.
He was with three men, and they were all track veterinarians.
And on the track season down there, Dr. Jagger had all the work to do, and it was mostly small animals, a lot of it small animals.
And Karsten Dyke, Chapman, I've forgotten the other man's name,
But I said Dr. Jange might be interested, and so he contacted him and he came.
He stayed there fromI came up here in 26, he stayed down there until 37.
Then he came up and took over veterinary hygiene.
And at the same time, Dr. Marsteller was dean, and he thought we needed a department of neuroparasitology.
So Dr. Turk took that over.
Now wait a minute, I may be wrong about this.
Dr. Turk took it over after Dr. Van Valkenburgh died.
So Dr. Van Valkenburgh took it over in 37.
until his death, and I don't recall that date.
I believe about 46, something like that.
I'm not positive.
By Dr. Van Valkenburgh, I had been down on research work in parasitology in the Indies, I believe, and I'd forgotten his work that he was doing when he came here.
but he was an excellent fine gentleman and a good teacher and he helped a lot.
Do you remember Dr. Wharton?
Arthur E. Wharton?
Indeed I do.
We came here together.
He's a product of Colorado and he took the job in 26 in
in pathology when I took the job in physiology and pharmacology.
Pathology then included parasitology and I guess you might say hygiene and let's see, I guess that takes it all, but he had the whole thing to do.
He was an associate professor in charge, and I recall in, let's see, in 36 when Dr. Francis died, I think it took a year, and then Dr. Marstall and Dr. Wharton couldn't get along too well.
So Wharton went to San Antonio, some crooked laboratories, I think.
But I'd have a letter from him or a wire once in a while, telephone conversation with him once in a while, inquiring about this or that.
And I saw him a couple of times before his death.
I don't recall what date.
I think Dr. Miller told me he was a rather unusual man.
Yes, he had married ten times.
Ten times?
That means only nine.
I remember wife number two and ten were the same person.
And she was the one who shot him.
Oh, that's right, yeah.
Yes, it was unusual.
I remember the occasion when we went with the whole student body down, which constituted only about 10 or 15, down to Sulphur Springs, downhill on the Navasota River, the bottoms.
And so we sat around the campfire, drank some strong coffee, and both of us were wide awake.
And some of the, two or three of the boys went with us, and I guess the boys wanted to go.
They wanted to go frog gigging and tramp through the woods.
And we left, I guess, must have been about twelve o'clock, something like that.
So it was about five o'clock before we got back.
And we got within about a hundred yards, and it was very dark.
And we'd call, and of course those boys in the camp wouldn't answer us.
And we were lost.
And so finally we heard the fire had gone down, and so we heard some of them laughing.
But he was a woodsman.
He had many guns, and he was a gun collector.
But a very strong man, very agile.
But he had some very good qualities.
But we never crossed each other.
I don't recall a single word of disagreement that we ever had.
But he did some things that I wouldn't have proved out, but I...
I don't ever recall having a conversation with Dr. Marstead or any of the higher authorities about him.
I think, I don't know who reported it, whether it was students of some of his activities, but he left in 37.
Let's turn to your career now.
in 1935 you were appointed head of the Department of Veterinary Physiology and Pharmacology, a position that you held for over three decades.
Why did they appoint you?
I can't answer that.
I recall once in about 1933 or something I had, at two different times I had
two different jobs offered to me.
